TY  - JOUR
T1  - A critique of the asset pricing theory's tests Part I: On past and potential testability of the theory
AU  - Roll, Richard
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 4
IS  - 2
SP  - 129
EP  - 176
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/03/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(77)90009-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X77900095
AB  - Testing the two-parameter asset pricing theory is difficult (and currently infeasible). Due to a mathematical equivalence between the individual return/‘beta’ linearity relation and the market portfolio's mean-variance efficiency, any valid test presupposes complete knowledge of the true market portfolio's composition. This implies, inter alia, that every individual asset must be included in a correct test. Errors of inference inducible by incomplete tests are discussed and some ambiguities in published tests are explained.
